# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 29, 1776.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The delegate from Hanover County Patrick Henry defeated Thomas Nelson Jr. and John Page.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election took place forty-five days after the adoption of the Lee Resolution by the Fifth Virginia Convention declaring the independence of the United Colonies from Great Britain.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Constitution of Virginia had been adopted by the convention the same day and went into effect immediately.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The new constitution called for the governor of Virginia to be elected by the votes of the Virginia General Assembly meeting in joint session.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Virginia Convention, as the provisional legislature of the commonwealth, performed this function in the election of 1776.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Prior to 1830, the governor served a term of one year, renewable no more than three times in a seven-year period.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Henry was reelected four times: twice consecutively in 1777 and 1778, and again in 1784 and 1785, to serve a total of five consecutive terms in office.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Fifth Virginia Convention convened in Williamsburg on May 6, 1776, amidst increasingly widespread support for independence among the Patriots who supported the American Revolution.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] On May 15, 1776, the convention approved a resolution instructing Virginia's delegates in the Second Continental Congress to support a formal declaration of independence absolving the Thirteen Colonies from their allegiance to the British Empire.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Congress voted to adopt the Lee Resolution on July 2, precipitating passage of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] While Congress debated independence, the Virginia Convention took action to establish the foundations for an independent commonwealth.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A Declaration of Rights was introduced in the convention on May 27 and adopted on June 12; on June 29, the delegates voted unanimously to adopt the proposed Constitution of Virginia.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] With the Constitution now in place, elections for governor and Attorney General proceeded immediately.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Constitution of 1776 called for the governor and other executive officers to be elected by a joint session of the General Assembly, with a majority of votes cast necessary to elect the governor.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The governor was elected for a term of one year and limited to three terms in a seven-year period.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] With the first General Assembly yet unelected, the Virginia Convention carried out the election of the first governor and Attorney General.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election was conducted by secret ballot; in all, 106 delegates to the Virginia Convention cast votes for governor.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Virginia Convention elected Henry by a majority of 60 electoral votes to 45 for his nearest competitor, Thomas Nelson.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] George Wythe, James Madison, Bartholomew Dandridge, and William Roscoe Wilson Curl were appointed to inspect the ballots and inform Henry of his election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was scheduled to be held in Virginia on May 29, 1777.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election] However, when the Virginia General Assembly met to conduct the election, the incumbent governor of Virginia Patrick Henry was the only candidate nominated.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election] By a joint resolution of the Senate and House of Delegates, balloting was dispensed with and Henry was declared re-elected by acclamation.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1778-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was scheduled to be held in Virginia on May 29, 1778.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 1, 1779.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The delegate from Albemarle County Thomas Jefferson defeated the president of the Council of State John Page.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Patrick Henry was ineligible for re-election due to term limits established by the Constitution of Virginia.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election was conducted by the Virginia General Assembly in joint session.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] No candidate had a majority after the first count, requiring a second ballot between the two top-finishers.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 2, 1780.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Thomas Jefferson was re-elected.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Senate and the House of Delegates met separately on June 1 to nominate candidates for governor; more than one nomination was made, requiring a vote of the Virginia General Assembly.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] When the Assembly met in joint session the following day, Jefferson was selected by the majority of members on the first ballot, although the names of the other candidates and the votes tallied were not recorded.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on November 20, 1782.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Benjamin Harrison V was re-elected.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The House of Delegates met on November 19 to make nominations for governor and other offices, which the Senate accepted without amendment; the rule disqualifying votes for candidates other than those nominated was repealed prior to the balloting.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Harrison was selected by a majority of members on the first ballot; the official record of the proceedings does not include the names or tallied votes for any other candidates.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1783-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on November 27, 1783.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1783-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The House of Delegates met on November 26 to make nominations for governor and other offices, which the Senate accepted without amendment.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1783-virginia-gubernatorial-election] On the day of the election, Harrison was selected by a majority of members on the first ballot; the official record of the proceedings does not include the names or tallied votes for any other candidates.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The **2012 United States presidential election in Virginia** took place on November 6, 2012, as part of the presidential election in which all 50 states plus the District of Columbia participated.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Virginia was won by Obama with 51.16% of the vote to Romney's 47.28%, a 3.88% margin of victory.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Third parties and write-ins received a cumulative 60,147 votes, representing 1.56% of the vote.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] In 2008, Obama won the state by 6.30%, becoming the first Democratic presidential nominee to win it since Lyndon B.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Johnson's nationwide Democratic landslide of 1964, but it had otherwise been a reliably Republican state prior to this.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] However, 2008 represented a realignment election for Virginia.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Much of the Democratic gains were attributed to the growth of progressive suburban Northern Virginia, particularly in Fairfax County, Loudoun County, and Prince William County, all of which voted for Obama twice despite becoming Republican strongholds after 1964.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The Northern Virginia suburbs are generally dominated by Washington, D.C., the most Democratic region in the country.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Obama's increased strength in this heavily populated region more than canceled out his weakness across rural Virginia, which, similar to the rest of Appalachia, swung towards the Republican Party in 2008 due to the Democrats' increasingly environmentalist policies.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Obama suffered a historically poor showing even in traditionally Democratic counties of Southwest Virginia, similar to his weak performance in neighboring West Virginia.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Having also won the state in 2008, Obama's 2012 victory made him the first Democrat since Franklin D.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Roosevelt in 1944 to carry Virginia in two consecutive elections.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] It also marked the first time since 1948 that the state voted Democratic in consecutive elections.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The Democratic margin of victory also made 2012 the first time since 1948 that Virginia voted more Democratic than the nation as a whole, albeit by a narrow advantage of 0.02%, thereby making the state the closest to the national results.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] These were ultimately signs of Virginia's continuing leftward shift, after it had been a mostly reliable state for Republicans on the presidential level since 1952.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Also, this election was the first since 1948 that Virginia voted for a different candidate than Indiana did.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] As of the 2024 presidential election, this was the last time the Republican nominee won Montgomery County, and the last time the Democratic nominee won the independent city of Covington along with Buckingham, Caroline, Essex, Nelson and Westmoreland counties.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] This was the last election that Virginia was considered to be a swing state.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Every subsequent Democratic presidential nominee has won the state by more than a 5% margin, as Virginia has transformed into a blue state.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] In 2016, the Republican nominee won the election without carrying Virginia for the first time since 1924.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] By 2024, Virginia voted for a Democrat who lost the popular vote, also for the first time since 1924.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Because incumbent Democratic President Barack Obama faced no serious opposition from within his party in seeking reelection, no Democratic primary was held.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The Republican primary took place on Super Tuesday, March 6, 2012.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Virginia had 49 delegates to the 2012 Republican National Convention including the unbound superdelegates.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] 33 delegates were awarded on a winner-take-all basis by congressional district.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The other 13 were awarded to the candidate who won a majority statewide, or allocated proportionally if no one got a majority.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Only Mitt Romney and Ron Paul appeared on the ballot.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Other candidates failed to submit the necessary 10,000 signatures (including at least 400 from each of the state's 11 congressional districts) required to get on the ballot by the deadline of 22 December 2011.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] On 27 December, Rick Perry filed a lawsuit – joined later by Michele Bachmann, Newt Gingrich, Jon Huntsman and Rick Santorum – in the federal District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia in Richmond that challenged provisions that determine who can appear on the primary ballot.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Gibney Jr. ruled on 29 December that he would not issue an injunction to stop the printing of ballots before a scheduled hearing on 13 January.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The Virginia Attorney General, Ken Cuccinelli, representing the state, made a motion to dismiss the case because of a lack of standing.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] On 13 January, Judge Gibney Jr. dismissed the lawsuit citing the equitable doctrine of laches ("sleeping on one's rights"), writing, "They knew the rules in Virginia many months ago...
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] In essence, they played the game, lost, and then complained that the rules were unfair." The United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit affirmed, emphasizing that the candidate plaintiffs' failure to file in a timely fashion required dismissal.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The final results saw Romney win with 59.54% and 43 delegates of the vote to Ron Paul's 40.46% and 3 delegates.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The initial polling in 2010 showed Obama leading with margins from 4 to 11 points.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] In September 2011, the tide changed, and Romney won every poll conducted from September 2011 to December 2011, except one.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] In January and February 2012, both candidates were neck and neck with neither having a decisive lead.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] In March, Obama was able to pull ahead and beat Romney in most polls until about late September 2012.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] On October 4, Romney won his first poll in a month, 48% to 45%.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Throughout October, Romney won every poll but one for nearly three weeks.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The latest polls in late October and early November shifted in Obama's favor, and Obama was able to successfully make the race near tied.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Although Romney had won the final poll by 2 points, 50% to 48%, the average of the last three polls showed Obama leading 49% to 48%.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Despite losing the state, Romney won seven of 11 congressional districts, while Obama won four, including one held by a Republican.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] This was the first election since 1976 in which Virginia did not vote in the same way as neighboring North Carolina, and the first election ever in which Virginia voted Democratic while North Carolina voted Republican, which has occurred again in every subsequent election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Virginia was the only state that backed Obama twice that didn't back Bill Clinton in either of his runs for president in 1992 and 1996.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Despite Indiana and neighboring North Carolina flipping back into the Republican column, Virginia remained in the Democratic column, voting for President Obama with a margin of 3.88%, albeit a reduced margin from 2008 when he carried it by 6.30%.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] 2008 was the first time a Democrat carried the state of Virginia since Lyndon B.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Johnson carried it in his landslide 1964 election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Republican support, which had been anchored by the historically Republican D.C. suburbs, dwindled as the population grew.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] According to 270toWin, Obama carried Northern Virginia by 59.8% to Romney's 38.8%, a 21% margin, a great improvement from Al Gore's 3.2% win against George W.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Bush in 2000 and John Kerry's 7.9% win against Bush in 2004.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The leftward shift of college-educated whites and dominance by the unabashedly liberal District of Columbia only furthered Democratic margins.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Widening margins in Northern Virginia allowed Obama to counteract losses in Southwest Virginia as the Democrats increasingly supported environmentalist policies making them unpopular amongst Appalachian voters.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Consequently, Democrats were able to comfortably carry it in every election following 2008: a Republican wouldn't win statewide public office in Virginia until Glenn Youngkin won the 2021 gubernatorial election.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] According to exit polls from The New York Times, voter demographics were split.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Romney carried men 51-47 while Obama carried women 54–45.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Men and women make up 47% and 53% of the electorate, respectively.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] While Romney expectedly carried white voters in a 61-37 landslide, Obama was able to offset these wins with 93–6, 64–33, and 66-32 landslides among African Americans, Hispanics, and Asians, respectively.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Cumulatively, these minorities consisted of 28% of the electorate.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Splits among age groups were also obvious: voters 18 to 29 and 30 to 44 favored Obama 61-36 and 54–45, respectively, while voters aged 46–64 favored the Republican ticket 53-44 and 65+ favored them 54–46.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Romney was able to carry three of four education groups: those with no, some, or a college degree favored Romney by narrow margins of 50–49, 51–47, and 50–48, respectively, but Obama canceled out these wins with a 57–42 win among postgraduates.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Respectively, these groups comprise 46%, 25%, 30%, and 24% of voters.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Self-identified moderates were carried by Obama 56–42, but Independents flipped back into the Republican column, backing Romney 54–43 after backing Obama by 1 percentage point in 2008.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Economic status also showed a clear political divide in exit polls.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The president's strength came from lower-income voters: he carried those with an income under $30,000 by 61-38 and an income $30,000 to $50,000 by 60–38.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] However, Romney's close win among the upper middle class was a good sign for Democrats: Bush carried them 57–43 in 2004, a 14-point win, and it solidified suburban Northern Virginia's shift left.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] In terms of county performance, Romney flipped two counties back into the Republican column, including Montgomery, home to Virginia Tech in Blacksburg.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] King and Queen County also returned to the Republican column, thereby making Obama the first Democrat to win the White House without carrying this county.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Obama racked up his greatest margins in independent cities, where he received upwards of 70% of the vote in many of them.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Petersburg gave 89.79% of its vote to the Democratic ticket.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] On the opposite end of the spectrum, Romney's best performances were in Southwest Virginia and the Shenandoah Valley, where he garnered over 60% of ballots cast.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Despite polls predicting a close race, Obama's comfortable margin in Virginia solidified the state's shift to the Democrats.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] In 2016, Democrat Hillary Clinton would win the state by 5.32% against Donald Trump, one of the few states where she improved on Obama's margins despite losing the election nationwide.
[src:2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] In 2020, Joe Biden won the state by 10.11%, the best margin for a Democrat since Franklin D.
